            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this calorie deficit calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed to be more transparent than many basic
                calorie calculators. It shows you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  your <strong>BMR</strong> (basal metabolic rate) using the
                  Mifflin–St Jeor equation,
                </li>
                <li>
                  your <strong>TDEE</strong> (total daily energy expenditure)
                  based on activity level,
                </li>
                <li>
                  a <strong>customizable calorie deficit</strong> and estimated
                  weekly weight change,
                </li>
                <li>
                  a <strong>realistic time frame</strong> to reach your goal
                  weight, and
                </li>
                <li>
                  a suggested <strong>macro breakdown</strong> (protein, carbs,
                  fat).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>BMR formula (Mifflin–St Jeor)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>For men:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMR} = 10 \times \text{weight}_{kg} + 6.25 \times
                  \text{height}_{cm} - 5 \times \text{age} + 5\)
                </p>
                <p><strong>For women:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMR} = 10 \times \text{weight}_{kg} + 6.25 \times
                  \text{height}_{cm} - 5 \times \text{age} - 161\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                BMR is the energy your body uses at rest for essential functions
                like breathing, circulation, and temperature regulation.
              </p>

              <h3>From BMR to TDEE</h3>
              <p>
                To estimate your <strong>TDEE</strong>, we multiply BMR by an
                activity factor:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Sedentary: \( \times 1.2 \)</li>
                <li>Lightly active: \( \times 1.375 \)</li>
                <li>Moderately active: \( \times 1.55 \)</li>
                <li>Very active: \( \times 1.725 \)</li>
                <li>Extra active: \( \times 1.9 \)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This gives an approximate number of calories you burn per day on
                average.
              </p>

              <h3>Calorie deficit and weekly weight loss</h3>
              <p>
                A calorie deficit means eating fewer calories than your TDEE.
                The calculator uses the common approximation:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\(1 \text{ kg fat} \approx 7{,}700 \text{ kcal}\)</p>
                <p>\(1 \text{ lb fat} \approx 3{,}500 \text{ kcal}\)</p>
              </div>
              <p>So if your daily deficit is \(D\) kcal:</p>
              <p class="formula-box">
                \(\text{Weekly weight change} \approx \dfrac{7 \times
                D}{7{,}700} \text{ kg/week}\)
              </p>
              <p>
                We then compare your current and goal weights to estimate how
                many weeks it might take to reach your target, assuming the same
                deficit is maintained.
              </p>

              <h3>Macro calculation</h3>
              <p>
                Once your calorie target is set, we apply your chosen macro
                split. For example, with the balanced preset (30% protein / 40%
                carbs / 30% fat):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \(\text{Protein grams} = \dfrac{0.30 \times
                  \text{Calories}}{4}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Carb grams} = \dfrac{0.40 \times \text{Calories}}{4}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Fat grams} = \dfrac{0.30 \times \text{Calories}}{9}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                We also show approximate protein grams per kg of body weight so
                you can check that you are in a muscle‑friendly range (often
                1.6–2.2 g/kg for fat loss).
              </p>

              <h2>What is a healthy calorie deficit?</h2>
              <p>For most adults, a sustainable calorie deficit is:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>300–500 kcal/day</strong> for slow, steady loss, or
                </li>
                <li><strong>500–700 kcal/day</strong> for moderate loss.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Larger deficits can work in the short term but increase the risk
                of:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>muscle loss,</li>
                <li>fatigue and poor workout performance,</li>
                <li>strong hunger and cravings, and</li>
                <li>nutrient deficiencies or hormonal issues.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                People with medical conditions, pregnant or breastfeeding women,
                and underweight individuals should not start a calorie deficit
                without professional guidance.
              </p>

              <h2>Tips for using your calorie deficit effectively</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Track trends, not single days.</strong> Weigh yourself
                  several times per week and look at the 2–4 week average.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Recalculate as you lose weight.</strong> Your TDEE
                  will decrease, so your original deficit may shrink over time.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Prioritize protein and resistance training.</strong>
                  They help preserve muscle while you lose fat.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Sleep and stress matter.</strong> Poor sleep and high
                  stress can slow progress and increase hunger.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Medical disclaimer</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is for general educational purposes and is not a
                substitute for personalized medical or nutritional advice.
                Equations like Mifflin–St Jeor and the 7,700 kcal/kg rule are
                estimates and may not reflect your exact energy needs. Always
                consult a qualified health professional before making major
                changes to your diet, exercise, or weight‑loss plan, especially
                if you have any medical conditions or take medication.
              </p>
            </section>
